entry.title: Support decoding multiple concatenated frames in ZstdSourceStream
entry.content:
A zstd-encoded stream is allowed to be composed of multiple concatenated

frames, unlike gzip and brotli content-encoding. The current

implementation will stop decoding after the first frame, since

ZSTD_decompressStream() returns after each frame. This CL fixes this

behavior to support decoding multiple concatenated frames using zstd.

entry.title: [Bookmarks] Catch more exceptions for partner bookmarks
entry.content:
The implementation of ContentResolver#query() for PartnerBookmarks may

fail with a wide variety of exception codes. Including:



* NullPointerException

* CursorWindowAllocationException

* SecurityException - permission denial



These amount to 1000s of crashes and are generally caused by faulty

OEM implementions of the query rather than anything Chrome can control.



Prevent this from crashing the browser by making the existing try-catch

generic.

entry.title: Always use opaque formats for image reader
entry.content:
AImageReader takes format during initialization and will enforce it. For

YUV formats it has logic to match first frame's format rather than

format passed in, but it's often not enough when format changes during

runtime or if the formats are not 8-bits.



AIMAGE_FORMAT_PRIVATE allows to avoid checks and according to docs [1]

still allows GPU usage, only limitation is cpu-mapping is not possible.



We never map those buffers so this CL switches to always use private

format (under kill-switch for safety).



[1] https://developer.android.com/ndk/reference/group/media#aimagereader_newwithusage

entry.title: jni_zero: Change name mangling scheme for CalledByNatives
entry.content:
The previous scheme:

* was kinda confusing since it made acronyms out of names

* didn't actually guarantee unique names

* encoded return types despite them not participating in overload resolution



The new scheme:

* Uses C++ overloads when the number of parameters is unique (often the case)

* Does not encode return types

* Uses full names for types, but removes package when possible

* Guarantees unique names



Updates all Chrome code that was using methods with mangled names.

entry.title: Use InlinedVector in /cc
entry.content:
Replace usages of base::StackVector with absl::InlinedVector. This is

not a pure rename, as the semantics are slightly different:



1. Methods like push_back() which were accessed with the -> operator in

StackVector are instead accessed with . with InlinedVector.

2. The .container() method is not needed with InlinedVector

3. InlinedVector's iterators are pointers, so bare "auto" cannot be used

with them.



Some files were including stack_container.h despite not using it. In

those cases remove the #include statement.



See also discussion thread in cxx@chromium.org:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/jTfqVfU-Ka0/m/caaal90NCgAJ

entry.title: Disable MSBB when the user enables an explicit passphrase
entry.content:
...and vice versa, for clients that have the

`kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos` feature flag enabled.



This is a bit tricky, since the explicit-passphrase state is only

known once the SyncEngine was initialized for the first time, and

the "unknown" state must be properly handled. In particular:

* When signing in, MSBB should end up in the correct state, once the

explicit-passphrase state becomes known. (I.e. enabled iff history

is on and explicit-passphrase is off.)

* During browser startup (for already signed-in users), it's important

that MSBB does *not* get changed, so that users can still manually

turn it on or off.

* When turning history or explicit-passphase on/off, the MSBB state

should be updated accordingly (e.g. MSBB gets enabled when history

is enabled and there's no custom passphrase, etc.)

* One particular edge case is if the user signs in while offline (or

the sync server is otherwise unreachable), and thus the sync engine

never gets initialized. In this case, the MSBB state gets finally

resolved only once the engine initialization happens - even if there

was a browser restart in between.



This is a followup to crrev.com/c/4669127.
